function getImagenPromptsJSON(targetaudience, reportText) {
  return `
Analyze the following Market Intelligence Report for the ${targetaudience} market.

The report is structured into exactly 12 sections. Your task is to generate a unique, highly descriptive, literal image generation prompt (max 150 words each) for EACH of the 12 sections in sequential order.

CRITICAL INSTRUCTION FOR DISTINCT IMAGES:
To guarantee the images are completely different from one another, you MUST mix the specific Section Heading with the ${targetaudience} category and the exact insight discussed in that section. Do not use generic ${targetaudience} imagery for every section. 

The 12 sections you must generate a prompt for are:
I. Macro Insight
II. The Core Pillars (The Market Foundation)
III. Thematic Clustering (The Market Segments)
IV. Breakout Trends & Disruptors
V. Brand vs. Non-Brand Distribution (Discovery vs. Loyalty)
VI. Brand Share of Voice & Affinity
VII. The Battleground (Comparisons & Rivalries)
VIII. Demographic & Persona Shifts
IX. Pain Points & Friction
X. Search Intent Breakdown (The Customer Journey)
XI. Price Sensitivity & Value Tiering
XII. Strategic Google Ads & YouTube Recommendations

CRITICAL RULE: Output ONLY a raw, valid JSON array of 12 strings. Do not use markdown blocks, headers, or any other text.

Example format:
[
  "Macro insight: A soaring line chart displayed on a modern smartphone, representing mobile app growth in the ${targetaudience} market, photorealistic.",
  "Brand vs Non-Brand: Two distinct customer paths diverging, one towards a famous ${targetaudience} storefront and one towards an open market, bright lighting."
]

Input Report Data:
${reportText}
`;
}

function getCustomInfographicPrompt(targetaudience, reportText) {
  return `
You are an Expert UI/UX Designer and Frontend Developer. I am providing you with a Market Intelligence Report and a ${targetaudience}.
Input Report Data: ${reportText}

Your objective is to transform this text report into a stunning, executive-ready, single-file HTML presentation featuring a tabbed navigation interface.

CRITICAL CONSTRAINTS & RULES:

SINGLE FILE: Output ONLY valid HTML. All CSS must be within a single <style> block, and all tab-switching logic must be within a single <script> block. No external CSS/JS dependencies.

TABBED INTERFACE LAYOUT (CRITICAL):
Instead of one long scrolling page, you MUST divide the 12 sections into 4 distinct Tabs following this exact distribution:
Tab 1 (Market Momentum): Contains 4 Sections - Macro Insight, The Core Pillars (The Market Foundation), Thematic Clustering (The Market Segments), and Breakout Trends & Disruptors.
Tab 2 (Competitive Landscape): Contains 4 Sections - Brand vs. Non-Brand Distribution (Discovery vs. Loyalty), Brand Share of Voice & Affinity, The Battleground (Comparisons & Rivalries), and Demographic & Persona Shifts.
Tab 3 (Audience Profiling): Contains 3 Sections - Pain Points & Friction, Search Intent Breakdown (The Customer Journey), and Price Sensitivity & Value Tiering.
Tab 4 (Strategic Media Recommendations): Only Contains 1 Section - Strategic Google Ads & YouTube Recommendations.
Build a clean, sticky tab navigation bar at the top of the page. Only one tab's content should be visible at a time. The active tab must be visually highlighted.

HEADING FORMATTING (CRITICAL):
Do not use numbering or Roman numerals for ANY of the section headings in the HTML. For example, render the heading simply as "Macro Insight" instead of "1. Macro Insight" or "I. Macro Insight".

LAYERED, BREATHABLE LAYOUT:
Within each tab, EVERY SECTION must have its own dedicated, full-width horizontal layer with generous vertical padding (padding: 60px 20px;). Alternate background colors (e.g., white #ffffff to off-white #f8f9fa). Use a 2-column flex or grid layout for each layer (Text/Insights/Data on one side, Visual on the other, alternating left/right as you scroll).

INJECTED VISUALS (CRITICAL):
You MUST use EXACTLY these placeholders for your 12 image sources. Do not use real URLs.
Format: <img src="IMG_PLACEHOLDER_1" alt="description" loading="lazy" style="width: 100%; border-radius: 16px; object-fit: cover; box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);">
Use "IMG_PLACEHOLDER_1" for the first section, "IMG_PLACEHOLDER_2" for the second, and so on up to "IMG_PLACEHOLDER_12".

DATA, EVIDENCE & INSIGHT EXTRACTION (CRITICAL RULE):
The informational text can be highly descriptive to provide deep context, but you MUST extract and display the concrete evidence for sure. You must not summarize away the hard data. For EVERY section, you MUST visually display the core AI insights and evidence from the report.
Sub-Category Exhaustiveness: For sections with multiple sub-categories (e.g., Thematic Clustering with multiple clusters), you MUST include the insights and the comprehensive 'Evidence' for EVERY single sub-category.
Keyword Evidence (Crucial): Extract the exact keyword examples provided under "Evidence" in the text for all clusters. Format every single keyword and its accompanying YoY percentage as a highly visible, styled CSS pill (e.g., <span class="keyword-pill">macbook m4 (16.87%)</span>) clustered neatly underneath or beside the main insight.
Key Insights: Style the specific "Key Insight" for each section as a highly visible, distinct floating card or heavily styled blockquote to make it the focal point of the text column.
Quantitative Data: You must extract the exact percentage splits and YoY growth numbers mentioned in the text and prominently display them using large typography (e.g., Big Numbers) or within the CSS visualizations.

CONTENT & DATA SPECIFICATIONS:
Proofread carefully to ensure absolutely no typos. Logic must be included to wrap long labels to prevent them from overlapping.

DESIGN LANGUAGE:
Fonts: Sans-serif system fonts (Inter, Helvetica Neue, system-ui).
Color Palette: Use Google color theme for accents and tags. Highlight the active navigation tab using a distinct Google Blue.

DIVERSE CSS-NATIVE VISUALIZATIONS:
Translate the relative numbers and exact percentages from the report text into pure CSS visual elements. Use the REAL data from the report, do not use dummy data:
Use CSS conic-gradient to create pie charts or donut charts for Share of Voice or Intent breakdowns.
Use flexbox to create segmented/stacked horizontal bar charts for "Brand vs. Non-Brand" or "Budget vs. Premium" splits, explicitly labeling the exact percentages.
Use color-coded stat cards or pill tags with up/down arrows for YoY growth.
`;
}
